Cilantro
Cilantro is used as a fresh herb topping in the hotpot.<SEP>Cilantro is added at the end for freshness and garnish, and can also be added during serving.<SEP>Cilantro is used as a fresh garnish sprinkled on top before serving.<SEP>Cilantro is added at the end as a garnish and flavor component.<SEP>Cilantro is a fresh herb added at the end for aroma and garnish.<SEP>Fresh coriander leaves used as a finishing herb, added just before serving.<SEP>Cilantro is a fresh herb, chopped and used both in the broth and as a condiment topping.

Oyster Mushroom
Oyster mushroom is one of the edible fungi used in the hotpot, prepared by tearing into strips.

Half-Hour Cooking Time
Half-hour cooking time refers to the total preparation and cooking duration for the dish.<SEP>Half-hour cooking time refers to the total duration required to prepare Bai Cai Fen Si Guo.<SEP>Half-Hour Cooking Time indicates the total duration required to prepare the dish.

Savory And Fresh
Savory and fresh is the described flavor profile of the Za Jun Hui Hotpot.

Hotpot
Hotpot is a category of dish and a communal dining style originating from Chinese culinary traditions, characterized by a simmering pot of seasoned broth placed at the table or stove, into which diners cook a variety of ingredients such as meats, vegetables, noodles, and other items during the meal. This interactive and shared method of cooking emphasizes collective participation, as each person selects and prepares their preferred ingredients directly in the central pot. The broth base varies widely by region and recipe, ranging from fish-based broths to specialized preparations like Ejiao Red Date Black Chicken Soup, underscoring hotpot’s adaptability and regional diversity.

Specific dishes such as Bai Cai Fen Si Guo, Fish Head Vegetable Hotpot, Fresh Soup Hotpot, Milk Sweet Corn Hotpot, and Mild Radish Pork Rib Hotpot all fall under the hotpot category, illustrating its broad scope and culinary flexibility. Additionally, Maruko Noodle Soup is also classified as a type of hotpot, further demonstrating the category’s inclusive nature across different ingredient combinations and flavor profiles. Regardless of the specific variation, hotpot consistently features the core elements of tableside or stovetop communal cooking, a shared pot of flavorful broth, and an interactive dining experience that blends social engagement with culinary enjoyment.<SEP>Hotpot is a cooking method where ingredients are simmered in a shared pot of broth at the table.<SEP>Hotpot refers to the type of dish being prepared, characterized by cooking various ingredients together in a simmering broth at the table or stove.>

Vermicelli
Vermicelli is a type of starch noodle added to the hotpot after being soaked in water.<SEP>Vermicelli is a starch-based hot pot ingredient served raw and cooked in the broth.<SEP>Vermicelli is a type of starch-based noodle used in the dish, soaked and blanched before being added to the pot.<SEP>Vermicelli is an ingredient used in Bai Cai Fen Si Guo, added in appropriate amounts.<SEP>Vermicelli is an optional ingredient, arranged on a serving plate for hotpot cooking.

Stewing
Stewing is the cooking method used to prepare the hotpot base, involving simmering chicken with aromatics.<SEP>Stewing is the primary cooking method used to prepare the fish broth, involving simmering fish bones and aromatics in water to extract flavor.<SEP>Stewing is the cooking method used, involving simmering all ingredients in a clay pot over low heat for about an hour.<SEP>Stewing is the cooking method used to prepare Ejiao Red Date Black Chicken Soup.<SEP>Stewing is the primary cooking method used to prepare the small intestine in this recipe.<SEP>Stewing is the primary cooking method used, involving simmering ingredients in liquid in a pressure cooker.<SEP>Stewing is the cooking method used to prepare the Mild Radish Pork Rib Hotpot.

Enoki Mushroom
Enoki mushroom is a type of edible fungus included in the hotpot, with roots trimmed and washed.<SEP>Enoki Mushroom is added to the hotpot as a vegetable ingredient.<SEP>Enoki mushroom is a slender white mushroom used in the soup, washed and trimmed at the base before cooking.>

Mushroom
Mushroom refers to a generic edible fungus used in the hotpot, cleaned with a brush and sliced without cutting through the base.

Seafood Mushroom
Seafood mushroom is a variety of edible fungus used in the hotpot, prepared by trimming the roots and washing.

Chicken Mushroom
Chicken mushroom is an edible fungus used in the hotpot, prepared by trimming roots and washing.

Crab-Flavored Mushroom
Crab-flavored mushroom is a type of edible fungus included in the hotpot, prepared by trimming roots and washing.

Sesame Oil
Sesame oil is a fragrant oil used in the dipping sauce.<SEP>Sesame Oil is used in适量to add fragrance to the meatball mixture.

Chili Oil
Chili oil is a spicy condiment used in the dipping sauce.<SEP>Chili oil is added to the hot pot for spiciness and flavor.<SEP>Chili oil is a seasoning that contributes heat and aroma to the dish.

White Sesame Paste
White sesame paste is a key component of the dipping sauce.

Cooking Wine
Cooking wine is used both in the broth and during chicken blanching to remove腥味(gamey odor).<SEP>Cooking wine is used to marinate fish slices and remove fishy odors, referred to as "liao" in the recipe.<SEP>Cooking Wine is used in an appropriate amount to marinate the spiny catfish.<SEP>Cooking Wine is used in适量to enhance the aroma and remove the meaty odor from the pork mince.<SEP>Cooking wine is used to remove unwanted odors and add depth to the broth.<SEP>Cooking Wine is an ingredient used to deodorize the fish head during preparation.

Pepper Powder
Pepper powder is added to the broth for seasoning.<SEP>Pepper powder is used as a seasoning in the marinade for Hot Pot Chicken.<SEP>Pepper powder is a spice added to the broth for seasoning.

Salt
Salt is a fundamental and versatile seasoning ingredient widely used in hotpot cuisine and related dishes to enhance and balance flavors. It plays a central role in seasoning both the hotpot broth and individual components such as meats, fish, and sauces. Specifically, salt is added in carefully measured amounts—often described as “appropriate” or “适量” (moderate quantity)—to marinate proteins like spiny catfish and chicken, as well as to season meat mixtures. In broth preparation, salt is typically introduced about two hours into a three-hour simmering process to achieve optimal savory depth, contributing to a well-rounded flavor profile in various soup bases, including fish-based broths and the Spicy Pork Rib and Radish Hotpot. Additionally, in dishes such as Bai Cai Fen Si Guo, salt serves as a basic yet essential seasoning to fine-tune the overall taste according to culinary or personal preference. Across all applications, salt is consistently regarded as a core element for flavor adjustment and balance in hotpot cooking.<SEP>Salt is used as a seasoning in Maruko Noodle Soup, added in appropriate amounts.<SEP>Salt is an ingredient added in appropriate amounts to season the Fresh Soup Hotpot.<SEP>Salt is an ingredient used to season the Mild Radish Pork Rib Hotpot.<SEP>Salt is used in appropriate amounts to season the broth of the hot pot.<SEP>Salt is used to season the broth to taste.<SEP>Salt is used as a basic seasoning in the soup.>

Onion
Onion is added to the broth for flavor.<SEP>Onion is minced and sautéed in butter to build flavor in the soup base of the hotpot.<SEP>Onion is used as an aromatic base, sautéed to build flavor in the broth.

Ginger And Scallion
Ginger and scallion are aromatics used in the broth to enhance flavor and remove odors.

Fresh Chicken
Fresh chicken is the primary protein used to make the hotpot base broth.

Dipping Sauce
Dipping sauce is a condiment mixture made from white sesame paste, sesame oil, chili oil, minced garlic, and fresh soy sauce for eating with the hotpot.<SEP>Dipping sauce is a condiment made from scallion oil, soy sauces, chicken bouillon, sesame seeds, and fresh scallions, served with the hotpot.<SEP>Dipping Sauce is a personalized condiment made for hotpot, often including cilantro.

Fresh Soy Sauce
Fresh soy sauce is an ingredient used in the dipping sauce for the hotpot.

Za Jun Hui Hotpot
Za Jun Hui Hotpot is a hotpot dish featuring a variety of mushrooms and chicken, prepared with a savory and fresh flavor profile.

Shiitake Mushroom
Shiitake mushroom is an edible fungus used in the hotpot, prepared by cutting a crosshatch pattern into the cap.<SEP>Shiitake mushrooms are soaked, cleaned, and layered into the hotpot for umami flavor.<SEP>Shiitake Mushroom is a type of mushroom used in the milk hotpot, prepared by removing the stem and scoring the cap.<SEP>Shiitake mushroom is a type of edible fungus used in the soup, soaked beforehand and cut into pieces.>

Minced Garlic
Minced garlic is used as an ingredient in the dipping sauce.

Chicken Broth
Chicken broth is the foundational soup base of the hotpot, made by stewing fresh chicken with aromatics.<SEP>Chicken broth is a savory liquid base for the hotpot, optionally substituted with bouillon cubes.<SEP>Chicken broth is a liquid base used in the recipe to form the soup component of the hotpot.

Hangbai Chrysanthemum
Hangbai chrysanthemum is a type of flower used in the tea base of the hotpot.

Brown Sugar
Brown sugar is added in small amounts to sweeten the tea base.

Honeysuckle
Honeysuckle is an herbal ingredient included in the tea mixture for the hotpot.

Goji Berries
Goji berries are used in the hotpot for their nourishing and beautifying properties.

Hawthorn
Hawthorn is an ingredient used in the Beauty Fruit Tea Hotpot, valued for its potential health benefits.

Licorice
Licorice is an ingredient included in the herbal tea base of the hotpot.

Rose Flower
Rose flower is used in the tea blend for its aromatic and beauty-enhancing qualities.

Beauty Fruit Tea Hotpot
Beauty Fruit Tea Hotpot is a sweet-flavored, health-focused hotpot dish designed for beauty and nourishment, prepared with herbal teas and fresh fruits.

Cucumber Peel
Cucumber peel is used as a decorative element at the base of the fruit arrangement.

White Radish
White radish serves as the structural base for arranging fruits into a floral bouquet.<SEP>White radish is cut into large chunks and stewed with pork ribs to add sweetness and texture.<SEP>White radish is a main ingredient in the dish, cut into large pieces and cooked with pork ribs.

Pear
Pear is one of the fruits used in the hotpot, cut into small pieces and skewered.

Apple
Apple is cut into small pieces, skewered, and used decoratively in the fruit arrangement.

Star Fruit
Star fruit is prepared by removing fibers, slicing, and skewering for the hotpot.

Red Grapes
Red grapes are washed and skewered as part of the fruit selection for the hotpot.

Cherry Tomato
Cherry tomato is used as both a fruit ingredient and a decorative element in the fruit bouquet.<SEP>Cherry Tomato is a small tomato variety used as a fresh ingredient in the milk hotpot.

Popcorn
Popcorn is served alongside the hotpot to counteract greasiness or provide a contrasting snack.

Lemon Slice
A lemon slice is added to the flower tea to enhance flavor.

Flower Tea Beverage
Flower tea beverage is prepared by steeping dried flowers with lemon and brown sugar in hot water, then heated on an alcohol stove to cook and warm the fruits.

Cooking Method
The cooking method for the Beauty Fruit Tea Hotpot is categorized as "other" and involves steeping flower tea and heating fruits on an alcohol stove.<SEP>The cooking method involves making douhua from soy milk using a coagulant, then preparing a hotpot broth with pickled vegetables and seasonings.<SEP>The cooking method used for this dish is boiling, typically done in a medium-sized clay pot.>

Preparation Time
The preparation time for the Beauty Fruit Tea Hotpot is approximately half an hour.

Alcohol Stove
An alcohol stove is used to keep the flower tea hot and to gently cook the skewered fruits during serving.

Flavor Profile
The flavor profile of the Beauty Fruit Tea Hotpot is sweet.

Dish Type
The dish type is classified as a hotpot, specifically a fruit and herbal tea-based variant.

Strawberry
Strawberries are washed, skewered, and also used to anchor the fruit bouquet on the white radish base.<SEP>Strawberry is a fruit used as a tea point ingredient, washed and briefly scalded with warm water before being cut for serving.

Silver Ear Fungus
Silver Ear Fungus is a type of edible fungus used in the dish, pre-soaked and cooked before serving.

Bread
Bread, specifically sesame bread, is sliced, toasted in an oven at 180°C for 5 minutes until crispy, and cut into small pieces for serving.

Beauty Slimming Tea Point Hotpot
Beauty Slimming Tea Point Hotpot is a type of hotpot dish designed for beauty and slimming purposes, served with various tea points and a creamy soup base.

Papaya
Papaya is a tropical fruit included as a tea point, peeled and cut into small pieces for consumption with the hotpot.

Red Date
Red Date (Jujube) is washed and briefly rinsed with warm water to avoid consuming raw water, then served as part of the tea points.<SEP>Red Date is an ingredient used in the preparation of Ejiao Red Date Black Chicken Soup, with a preference noted for Hetian dates from Xinjiang.

Cake
Cake, specifically chiffon cake, is prepared as a tea point by cutting it into small pieces to accompany the hotpot.

data.content:
Shuan Cai He Tang Er Bu Wu
Shuan Cai He Tang Er Bu Wu is a culinary concept meaning "simultaneously enjoying hotpot and soup," exemplified by the dish Sheng Gun Yu Pian Huo Guo.

Almond

data.entity_name: Sheng Gun Yu Pian Huo Guo
data.content:
Sheng Gun Yu Pian Huo Guo
Sheng Gun Yu Pian Huo Guo is a hotpot dish featuring fresh fish slices and a creamy fish broth, served with various vegetables and dipping sauce.

Fish Flavor
Fish flavor refers to the dominant taste profile of the dish, derived from fresh fish and seasonings like ginger, white pepper, and fermented sauces.<SEP>Fish Flavor refers to the characteristic taste profile of the dish, derived primarily from the fish head and complementary seasonings.

Ginger
Ginger (姜) is an aromatic root widely utilized in the preparation of hotpot and related dishes for its distinctive flavor, warmth, and aromatic qualities. It is incorporated at multiple stages of cooking: during the initial preparation of the fish or chicken broth, in marinades for proteins such as chicken, and again when reheating the soup for serving. Ginger may be used in various forms—including sliced (typically around 10g when specified), minced, or as part of a ginger-garlic paste—depending on the specific step in the recipe. Its primary culinary contributions are to impart a warm, pungent aroma and to enhance the overall depth of flavor in both the broth and marinated ingredients. Consistently valued across these applications, ginger serves as a foundational aromatic component in the hotpot base and associated preparations.<SEP>Ginger is minced and used to add warmth and aroma to the broth.<SEP>Ginger is an ingredient sliced and used to add aroma during cooking.<SEP>A rhizome used in multiple stages: for marinating fish, as slices in cooking, and as garnish.

Three-Quarter Hour
Three-quarter hour refers to the total cooking time of approximately 45 minutes required to prepare the dish.<SEP>Three-quarter hour refers to the total cooking duration of 45 minutes for the dish.

Carrot
Carrot is finely chopped and sautéed as part of the soup base preparation for the hotpot.<SEP>Carrot is sliced and added to the hotpot as a vegetable component.

Potato
Potato is peeled, cubed, and cooked with pumpkin to form the base of the creamy soup.

Pumpkin
Pumpkin is peeled, cubed, and cooked until soft to create a smooth, creamy soup base.

Pepper
Pepper is used in small amounts to season the soup base of the hotpot.<SEP>Pepper (胡椒粉) is used as a seasoning to add mild heat and depth to the hotpot broth.

Original Stock
Original Stock is a pre-packaged broth (1.5 boxes) used as the liquid base for the soup.

White Pepper
White pepper is a spice used both in the broth and in marinating the fish slices for flavor and aroma.

Whipping Cream
Whipping Cream (50g) is added to the blended soup to enrich its texture and flavor.

Japonica Rice
Japonica rice is a short-grain rice added to the strained fish broth and pressure-cooked into a thick porridge base for the hotpot.

Salad Oil
Salad oil is used for frying fish bones and making the葱oil-based dipping sauce.

Black Fish
Black fish (Wuchang fish or snakehead fish) is the main protein source, used for both broth and sliced raw fish.

Scallion
Scallion (大葱), a type of green onion, is widely used in culinary applications for its aromatic and flavorful properties. It serves multiple roles across various stages of cooking: as a fresh garnish—particularly in dipping sauces—and as a key ingredient in marinades, where it imparts fragrance to proteins such as chicken. During the cooking process, scallion is utilized both in minced form for seasoning and in segmented form, as exemplified by the use of 20g portions when stewing pork ribs. It also functions as an aromatic base when sautéed, contributing depth to broths and hotpot bases. Additionally, scallion is processed into scallion oil, further extending its utility as a flavoring agent. Across these diverse applications, scallion consistently enhances dishes through its distinctive aroma and taste.<SEP>Scallion is used as a seasoning in the dish, added at the end for flavor and garnish.<SEP>Scallion is an ingredient used in the Fresh Soup Hotpot, cut into segments.<SEP>Green onions cut into segments, used for aroma and garnish.

White Sesame Seeds
White sesame seeds are sprinkled into the dipping sauce for aroma and texture.

Chicken Bouillon
Chicken Bouillon is a seasoning commonly used in various dishes to enhance umami flavor. It is specifically added to recipes such as Bai Cai Fen Si Guo and hotpot to enrich the savory depth of the overall taste. In some contexts, it is referred to as "Jing" or "Essence," highlighting its role as a concentrated flavoring agent. Chicken Bouillon is also incorporated into meat mixtures and dipping sauces, where it functions similarly to monosodium glutamate (MSG) by amplifying umami notes. The quantity used is typically described as "适量" (an appropriate or moderate amount), indicating its use is calibrated to balance and complement other ingredients without overpowering them. Across all applications, its primary culinary purpose remains consistent: to intensify and round out the savory flavor profile of the dish.

Butter
Butter (30g) is melted in the pot to sauté onions and build the flavor foundation of the soup.

Raisin
Raisin is prepared as one of the tea point ingredients to be served with the hotpot.

One-Hour Cooking Duration
The dish requires approximately one hour to prepare and cook.

Grape
Grape (specifically raisins) is listed as a prepared ingredient among the tea points to be served with the hotpot.

Hotpot Cooking Method
Hotpot Cooking Method involves preparing a creamy soup base and serving it in a heated pot with various tea points for dipping or pairing.<SEP>Hotpot Cooking Method involves simmering a flavored broth at the table and cooking various raw ingredients by dipping them into the boiling liquid.

Light Soy Sauce
Light soy sauce is used in the dipping sauce to provide saltiness and umami.<SEP>Light soy sauce is used for seasoning in the hotpot broth.

Spinach
Spinach is a leafy green vegetable used as a hotpot ingredient for涮cooking.<SEP>Spinach is a leafy green vegetable added to the hotpot for color, nutrition, and texture.<SEP>Spinach is one of the leafy greens that can be added to the hot pot.

Snow Peas
Snow peas (or Holland beans) are a crisp vegetable added to the hotpot for texture and color.

Bunashimeji Mushrooms
Bunashimeji mushrooms (white beech mushrooms) are a type of edible fungus used as a hotpot ingredient.

Button Mushrooms
Button mushrooms (or portobello immature form) are used as a hotpot ingredient for their mild flavor and texture.<SEP>Button Mushrooms are a vegetable topping served with the hotpot.

Taihu White Shrimp
Taihu white shrimp are freshwater shrimp from Lake Taihu, added to the hotpot as a protein-rich ingredient.

Fish Porridge
Fish porridge is a thick, creamy base made by pressure-cooking fish broth with japonica rice, serving as the hotpot soup base.

Steamed Fish Soy Sauce
Steamed fish soy sauce is a seasoned soy sauce used in the dipping sauce for depth of flavor.

Flavor Enhancer
Flavor enhancer (Tiaowei Xian) is used to boost the overall taste of the hot pot.<SEP>Flavor enhancer is a seasoning used to enrich the taste of the soup base.<SEP>Flavor Enhancer is a seasoning used to intensify the umami taste of the dish.

Taro Slices
Taro slices are prepared by peeling taro and grating it into slices, then frying them briefly before adding to the hot pot.

Fermented Black Bean Sauce
Fermented black bean sauce is a seasoning used to flavor the Lamb and Taro Hot Pot.

Lamb Spare Ribs
Lamb spare ribs are a main ingredient in the Lamb and Taro Hot Pot, used after being blanched and pressure-cooked.

Spicy Numbing Seasoning
Spicy numbing seasoning (Malaxian) contributes to the signature mala (numbing and spicy) flavor profile.

Dried Chilies
Dried chilies are added to the broth to enhance heat and aroma.<SEP>Dried chilies are chopped, rinsed, and dried before being stir-fried to add heat and aroma.

Shiitake Mushrooms
Shiitake mushrooms are cleaned and added to the hot pot for umami flavor and texture.

Taro
Taro is the root vegetable used to make taro slices, a key component of the dish.

Lamb And Taro Hot Pot
Lamb and Taro Hot Pot is a spicy, numbing hot pot dish featuring lamb spare ribs and fried taro slices, cooked over about an hour.

Wood Charcoal
Wood charcoal is used during the blanching step to remove undesirable odors from the lamb spare ribs.

Boiling
Boiling is a fundamental cooking method characterized by the immersion and simmering of ingredients in a hot liquid, typically water or broth, until cooked through. In the context of various dishes, boiling serves as the primary technique for preparing multiple hotpot-style meals and soups. Specifically, it is the main method used to prepare the Lamb and Taro Hot Pot, the Spicy Sour Dumpling Hotpot—where ingredients are simmered in a flavorful broth—and the Fish Head Vegetable Hotpot. Boiling is also employed in making Bai Cai Fen Si Guo and general hotpot preparations, including the cooking of meatballs within the broth. Additionally, Maruko Noodle Soup relies on boiling, with its components simmered in water to develop flavor and achieve desired texture. Across these applications, boiling consistently functions as the central culinary process that defines the preparation and character of these liquid-based dishes.<SEP>Boiling is the cooking method used to prepare the Fresh Soup Hotpot.<SEP>Boiling is the cooking method used to prepare the Milk Sweet Corn Hotpot.<SEP>Boiling is the primary cooking method used to prepare the pork ribs and assemble the hot pot.<SEP>Boiling is the cooking method used to prepare the Spicy Fish Head Tofu Hotpot.

Mala
Mala refers to the characteristic numbing and spicy flavor profile of the dish, achieved through specific seasonings like chili oil and spicy numbing seasoning.

Ginger Slices
Ginger slices are added when pressure-cooking the lamb spare ribs to enhance flavor and reduce gaminess.<SEP>Ginger slices are used to add warmth and fragrance during the initial stir-frying stage.<SEP>Ginger slices are added during stewing to enhance flavor and remove residual odors from the small intestine.

Five-Spice
Five-spice is a flavor profile used in the Hot Pot Chicken recipe, imparting a distinctive aromatic taste.<SEP>Five-spice is the flavor profile of the Mild Radish Pork Rib Hotpot.

Dried Chili
Dried chili is a seasoning ingredient used to add spiciness to the Hot Pot Chicken.<SEP>Dried chili is added when reheating the broth for hotpot to provide mild heat and flavor.<SEP>Dried chili is used to add heat and aroma to the hotpot base.<SEP>Dried Chili is used to add spiciness to the hotpot and is cooked with the fish head for 20 minutes.<SEP>Dried red chili peppers used to add heat and fragrance to the dish.

Hot Pot Chicken
Hot Pot Chicken is a Chinese dish prepared using hot pot cooking method with chicken legs and various seasonings and ingredients.

Soy Sauce
Soy sauce is a liquid seasoning used in marinating the chicken and enhancing umami flavor.<SEP>Soy Sauce is a seasoning ingredient used in适量(appropriate amount) for flavoring the meat mixture.<SEP>A liquid condiment used to enhance umami and saltiness in the dish.

Chicken Leg
Chicken leg is a primary ingredient in Hot Pot Chicken, cut into pieces and marinated before cooking.

Hot Pot
Hot pot is the cooking method used to prepare Hot Pot Chicken, involving simmering ingredients in a shared pot at the table.<SEP>Hot pot is the category or style of the dish, involving a simmering broth into which ingredients are added and cooked at the table.

Five-Spice Powder
Five-spice powder is a spice blend used in marinating the chicken for Hot Pot Chicken.

Maggi Seasoning
Maggi seasoning (Mei Ji Xian) is a umami-rich liquid seasoning used in the marinade.

Garlic
Garlic is used to add aroma and flavor, first sautéed in oil during cooking.<SEP>Garlic is used in the form of ginger-garlic paste or fresh garlic to add aroma and flavor during cooking.<SEP>Garlic (蒜) is used in the hotpot broth for aromatic flavor.<SEP>Garlic is a pungent bulb used to enhance the savory flavor of the hotpot base.<SEP>Garlic is minced and used to build aromatic depth in the hotpot base.<SEP>Garlic is an ingredient sliced and used to add aroma during cooking.<SEP>Bulbs of Allium sativum, crushed and used for aromatic base in the dish.

Kelp
Kelp is a seaweed-based hot pot ingredient served raw and cooked in the broth.<SEP>Kelp is cleaned, blanched, and stewed with pork ribs to form the base broth.<SEP>Kelp, specifically fresh kelp roots, is used as a hotpot ingredient.

Beef Tripe
Beef tripe (Mao Du) is a hot pot ingredient served raw and cooked in the broth.

Octopus
Octopus (referred to as "Ba Dai Shao") is a涮(hot pot) ingredient served raw and cooked at the table.

Clay Pot
A clay pot is used to simmer the chicken and broth for 30 minutes before serving as a hot pot.<SEP>A clay pot is the cooking vessel used for preparing the dish, requiring low heat and covered焖cooking.<SEP>A medium-sized clay pot is the cooking vessel used to prepare the soup.>

Cabbage
Cabbage is a vegetable hot pot ingredient served raw and cooked in the broth.

Peanut Oil
Peanut oil is used for sautéing aromatics at the beginning of the cooking process.

Cooking Time
Cooking time refers to the total duration required to prepare Hot Pot Chicken, which is one hour.<SEP>Cooking time refers to the total active preparation and cooking duration specified for the recipe, noted as ten minutes.<SEP>Cooking Time refers to the duration required to prepare the dish, specified as several hours, with a slow simmer of 1.5–2 hours for the broth.<SEP>Cooking Time refers to the total duration of about half an hour required to prepare the Mild Radish Pork Rib Hotpot.<SEP>Cooking time refers to the duration required to prepare the dish, which is half an hour for Spicy Fish Head Tofu Hotpot.

Chicken Leg Mushroom
Chicken leg mushroom is an edible fungus used as a hot pot ingredient.

Larou Shan Yao Hotpot
Larou Shan Yao Hotpot is a hotpot dish with a savory and fresh taste, prepared by stewing for about an hour.

Shan Yao (Chinese Yam)
Shan Yao, or Chinese yam, is a key ingredient in the dish, used in 300-gram portions and cut into small pieces.

Bok Choy Leaves
Bok choy leaves are used in the dish, with three leaves added either chopped or torn.

Dried Shiitake Mushrooms
Dried shiitake mushrooms are used in the dish, with "several pieces" added.

Homemade Dried King Oyster Mushrooms
Homemade dried king oyster mushrooms are included in the recipe in an unspecified quantity.

Larou (Cured Pork)
Larou is a type of cured pork used as a main ingredient in the dish, amounting to 200 grams.

Water
Water is added in an appropriate amount as a base liquid for stewing the hotpot.<SEP>Water is used in appropriate amounts for soaking pork ribs and as the base liquid for stewing and the hotpot.<SEP>Water is added gradually to the pork mince during meatball preparation to develop elasticity and increase volume.

Pickled Mustard Greens
Pickled mustard greens are a key ingredient, prepared by soaking, draining, chopping, and sugar-marinating before cooking.<SEP>Pickled Mustard Greens are added to the hotpot base in an appropriate amount for sour flavor.

Enoki Mushrooms
Enoki mushrooms are a type of edible fungus used in the recipe, cleaned, trimmed, and separated before cooking.<SEP>Enoki mushrooms are slender, delicate mushrooms used to add umami and texture to the dish.<SEP>Enoki Mushrooms are a type of mushroom used in the hotpot.

data.entity_name: Shui Zhu Suan Cai Xing Bao Gu Fen Si Pot
data.content:
Shui Zhu Suan Cai Xing Bao Gu Fen Si Pot
Shui Zhu Suan Cai Xing Bao Gu Fen Si Pot is a spicy and numbing vegetarian hot pot dish featuring pickled vegetables, enoki mushrooms, king oyster mushrooms, and vermicelli.

Homemade Ingredient Dish
Homemade ingredient dish refers to a meal prepared from scratch using raw, unprocessed components, as described in the recipe.

Spicy And Numbing
Spicy and numbing is the characteristic flavor profile of the dish, derived from ingredients like Sichuan peppercorns and chili.

Sichuan Peppercorns
Sichuan peppercorns are used to impart the characteristic numbing sensation in the dish.<SEP>Sichuan peppercorns (花椒) are used in the hotpot base for their numbing and aromatic qualities.

Star Anise
Star anise is a spice used in the recipe to add aromatic depth.<SEP>Star anise is used in the initial broth preparation to infuse aromatic depth.

Celery
Celery is washed, cut into segments, and added toward the end of cooking for texture and freshness.<SEP>Celery is chopped and added to the broth for aromatic depth.

Pixian Doubanjiang
Pixian Doubanjiang is a fermented broad bean and chili paste used to build flavor and create red oil in the base.<SEP>A fermented broad bean and chili paste from Pixian, China, used to add depth and red oil to the sauce.

King Oyster Mushrooms
King oyster mushrooms are a meaty mushroom variety, halved and thinly sliced for the dish.

Vegetarian
Vegetarian indicates the dish contains no animal products and is considered healthy and light.

Sugar
A small amount of sugar is used to balance flavors and is slowly caramelized during cooking.<SEP>Sugar is added in small amounts to balance the sour and spicy flavors of the hotpot.<SEP>Sugar is used in the recipe to balance flavors.<SEP>Sugar is added to enhance the sweet flavor of the dish.

Tomato
One tomato is used in the recipe, diced and stir-fried to produce red oil for flavor.<SEP>Tomato is used both as a fresh ingredient (1 whole, diced) and contributes to the broth's base flavor along with tomato paste.

Dried Orange Peel
